# Dependency Hygiene — Think Before You Install

## Before installing anything

Answer these first — out loud in your response:

```
DEPENDENCY CHECK
────────────────
Package I want to install: [name]
What it does: [one sentence]
Already in package.json that does this: [check before answering]
Last published on npm: [if over 12 months ago — flag it]
Weekly downloads: [under 10k is a risk — flag it]
Bundle size: [check bundlephobia.com — flag anything over 50kb]
Native alternative: [can this be done in 5 lines without a package?]
```

If something already in `package.json` does this — stop. Use what's there.
If it can be written natively in 5 lines — stop. Write it.

---

## Hard rules

- [ ] Never install a package to do something JavaScript/TypeScript handles natively
- [ ] Never install two packages that solve the same problem
- [ ] Never install a package with no activity in 12+ months without flagging it to the user
- [ ] Tooling and build tools always go in `devDependencies` — never in `dependencies`
- [ ] After every install, run `npm audit` — if any HIGH or CRITICAL vulnerabilities appear, remove the package and find an alternative
- [ ] After every install, run `npm run build` — if it breaks, remove it immediately

---

## Common traps to avoid

| Temptation | Reality |
|---|---|
| Installing `lodash` for one function | Use native array/object methods |
| Installing `moment` for date formatting | Use `date-fns` or native `Intl` |
| Installing `axios` when `fetch` exists | Use `fetch` — it is built in |
| Installing a UI library for one component | Build the component |
| Installing `uuid` | Use `crypto.randomUUID()` — built in |
| Two HTTP clients in the same project | Pick one and remove the other |

---

## After installing

- [ ] `npm audit` — zero HIGH or CRITICAL issues
- [ ] `npm run build` — still compiles clean
- [ ] Bundle size is justified by the value the package provides
- [ ] Added to the correct section (`dependencies` vs `devDependencies`)

---

## The rule in one line

If you can write it in 5 lines — write it. If you must install — prove nothing already does it and it has no known vulnerabilities.
